\f0\i0\b\fs32 \cf2 Constantly listening to changes of values\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 \
In some cases it might be required to constantly listening to the "outside" world for signals (new values). This listening always happens in the background. Whenever the value is updated using the Hippocrates API it can be handled using event handlers like 
\f2\i after <valued> changed
\f1\i0 .\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\i\b \cf2 \{listen\}::\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i0\b0 \cf2 listen for \\value\\. [>\
  [\\decision tree\\ >]\
    reject|accept \\value\\. [<]\
<]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 \ul \ulc2 Rules:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone 1. 
\f0\b reject \\value\\
\f1\b0  and 
\f0\b accept \\value\\
\f1\b0  must be used pairwise. If either statement is used the other must be used in another block.\
2. The two statements cannot be used in the same innermost paragraph.\
3. The validation rules of 
\f0\b \\value\\
\f1\b0  are executed before entering  
\f0\b \\decision tree\\
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b \cf2 reject \\value\\.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \
This statement rejects the value. The value will not be stored.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b \cf2 accept \\value\\.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i\b0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 This statement accepts the value. The value will be stored and the change event is triggered.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Examples:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone \
The following example listens to signals coming from a specific disposable device. To make sure that the right signal is captured the script filters by the MAC address. This example would be typical for an automatically generated script.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf2 during plan >\
  
\f5\b \ul listen for inhaler use >\

\f4\b0 \ulnone     assess device ID for inhaler use >\
      "01:23:45:67:89:ab" > 
\f5\b \ul accept inhaler use.
\f4\b0 \ulnone  <\
      in all other cases > 
\f5\b \ul reject inhaler use.
\f4\b0 \ulnone  <<<\
<\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

