\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 Referencing other definitions\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 \
Hippocrates will also supports referencing definitions. This will help script authors to reference either full definitions or partial definitions. What happens is that Hippocrates uses exactly the same descriptions that are is the referenced values. \
\
The sentences used for referencing other definitions are:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b \cf2 \{reference sentence\}::\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 definition is the same as for \\value\\.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf2 \{reference sentence with exception\}::\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i0\b0 \cf2 definition is the same as for \\value\\ except >\
  \{\{\\changed paragraph\\\}\}\
).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Rules:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone 1. References can only be used within a 
\f0\b \\paragraph\\
\f1\b0 .\
2. Exceptions can only be defined for full 
\f0\b \\paragraph\\
\f1\b0 .\
3. A 
\f0\b \\reference sentence\\
\f1\b0  can be used within an a 
\f0\b \\reference sentence with exception\\
\f1\b0 .\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Example:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone Let's take an example where pain levels at different points of the body should be recorded. While the position changes, the definition of pain is the same for each of the pain points.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf2 "pain in left arm" is a number (\
  valid value >\
    criteria >\
      value is 0.0?\
      value is between(1.0 ... 10.0)?\
    assess number of applying criteria >\
      0 .. 1 > no action. <\
      2      > value is valid. <<\
  <\
\
  references >\
    human > somatic symptoms <\
    human > body > left arm. <<\
  <\
\
  meaning >\
    assess value >\
               0.0 > value is not applicable. \
                      meaning is "not applicable". <\
      1.0 ...  2.0. > meaning is "no pain". best value. <\
      2.1 ...  8.0. > meaning is "moderate pain". <\
      8.1 ... 10.0. > meaning is "severe pain". worst value. <<\
  <\
\
  question >\
    ask patient "What is the level of pain in your left arm".\
  <\
<\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf2 \
Now, we would also like to know pain the right arm and both legs. To define the value that capture these pain levels referencing if used.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i0 \cf2 "pain in right arm" is a number >\
  
\f5\b \ul definition is the same as for pain in left arm except\ulnone  >\

\f4\b0     references >\
      human. > somatic symptoms. <\
      human. > body. > right arm. <<\
    <\
    question >\
      ask patient "What is the level of pain\
        in your right arm". <\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b \cf2   <\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 <\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 \ul \ulc2 Example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 If the difference between two value is too big, but some definition should be used, partial referencing can be used.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf2 "any value" is a value. >\
  valid units >\
    assess unit > \'b0C; \'b0F > unit is valid. <<<\
  ...\
<\
\
"other value" is a value >\
  valid units >\
    
\f5\b \ul definition is the same as for any value.\ulnone  <
