\f1\i0 \cf10 \ul \ulc10 Rules:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf10 \ulnone 1. Whenever either 
\f2\i \cf10 extend duration of <period> to \{period of time\} 
\f1\i0 \cf10 or 
\f2\i \cf10 extend duration of <period> by \{period of time\} 
\f1\i0 \cf10 are used 
\f2\i \cf10 maximum duration of <period> is \{period of time\} 
\f1\i0 \cf10 must be defined.\
2. A duration <
\f2\i \cf10 period>
\f1\i0 \cf10  can only be extended if an end is defined.\
3. Periods that only have a start defined cannot be extended.\
4. If a <
\f2\i \cf10 period> 
\f1\i0 \cf10 has already ended and the extended period also ends before the current time and date no value will be changed.\
5. If the value given for 
\f2\i \cf10 \{period of time\}
\f1\i0 \cf10  would end the period in the past the value is adjusted to end the period 
\f2\i \cf10 now
\f1\i0 \cf10 .\
6. If the value given for 
\f2\i \cf10 \{period of time\}
\f1\i0 \cf10  would lead to a period longer than the 
\f2\i \cf10 maximum duration of <period>
\f1\i0 \cf10  the maximum duration for the period is be used.\
7. The value of 
\f2\i \cf10 \{period of time\}
\f1\i0 \cf10  must be greater than the value used in the original definition of <
\f2\i \cf10 period>
\f1\i0 \cf10 .\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

