\f5\i0\b \cf2 \{validity of value\}::\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf2 value is valid. |\
value is not valid.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\i0 \cf2 \ul \ulc2 Rules:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone 1. 
\f0\b value is valid
\f1\b0  must be used at least once.\
2. If 
\f0\b \\value\\
\f1\b0  is a number or a time ranges (either based on 
\f0\b \\range selector\\
\f1\b0  or 
\f0\b between
\f1\b0  expressions) must not overlap or be completely within the range of another specified range.\
3. In case more than one unit is defined for 
\f0\b \\value\\
\f1\b0  can be used and conversion rules for units are defined the same unit must be used in all validation expressions.\
4. In case no conversion for units are defined the keyword 
\f0\b unit
\f1\b0 |
\f0\b units
\f2\i\b0  
\f1\i0 replaces the actual unit.\
5. In case \\
\f0\b value\\
\f1\b0  is a number all numbers used in validation expression must have the same precision. This precision is also used for input precision (see Hippocrates API).\
6. If a validation rules contains a reference to a 
\f0\b \\value\\
\f1\b0  all values must be part of a 
\f0\b \\value group\\
\f1\b0 .\
7. If an 
\f0\b \\assessment questions\\
\f1\b0  is based on other values these values must be within the value boundaries of 
\f0\b \\value\\
\f1\b0 .\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Example(s):\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone The following example shows the validation of 
\f0\b systolic blood pressure
\f1\b0  which has two conditions. One is the general range and another one is the dependency to 
\f0\b diastolic blood pressure
\f2\i\b0  
\f1\i0 which must be lower. Please note, that this dependency is only possible if 
\f0\b systolic blood pressure
\f1\b0  and 
\f0\b diastolic blood pressure
\f1\b0  are part of a value group (in this case 
\f0\b blood pressure
\f1\b0 ).\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf2 "systolic blood pressure" is a number >\
  intended use > \
    for use in value group only. <\
  valid units >\
    assess unit >\
      "mm/Hg" > unit is valid. <<<\
 
\f5\b  \ul valid values >\ulnone \
