\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Example(s)\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \ulnone A value can have many different interpretations that could depend from other values. In the following example the respiratory rate will be assessed. As the assessment is dependent on the age these distinctions will be made. Please not that Hippocrates will make the decision if questions about age need to be raised or not. When using the assessment in a script instead of using the actual numerical number the meaning of that value can be used. This increases readability and reduces potential errors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i0 \cf2 "respiratory rate" is a number >\
  valid units >\
    in case unit is one of ("breaths per minute"; "bpm") >\
      unit is valid. \
      1 breaths per minute = 1 bpm.\
      1 bpm = 1 breaths per minute. <\
  <\
\
  valid values >\
    in case value is between (0 bpm ... 100 bpm) >\
      value is valid. <\
  <\
\
 
\f5\b  \ul meaning >\

\f4\b0 \ulnone     assess age >\
      0 years >\
        assess pediatric age >\
          0 months ... 2 months >\
            assess value >\
               0 bpm ...  19 bpm >\
                         
\f5\b \ul meaning of value = "critically low".
\f4\b0 \ulnone  <\
              20 bpm ...  29 bpm >\
                         
\f5\b \ul meaning of value = "low".
\f4\b0 \ulnone  <\
